cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.CG, cs.GT, cs.CC. 

The paper deals with graph theory and algorithms for finding certain sets of vertices in graphs. This suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.DM (discrete mathematics), cs.CG (computational geometry), cs.GT (computational complexity and cryptography), and cs.CC (computational complexity). Among these, cs.DS and cs.DM seem the most likely, as the paper focuses on algorithmic and combinatorial aspects of graph theory. The use of modular decomposition, which is a tool for analyzing the structure of graphs, also suggests that cs.CG could be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the fact that the paper presents an approximation algorithm for a graph problem could make cs.GT and cs.CC relevant as well.
